text.tspan: Modular Robotics
Srijal Poojari, Madhav Wagh, Mentor: Pushkar Raj, Aditya Panwar, Fayyaz Pocker
e-Yantra Summer Internship Project 2017
This project is about homogeneous modular robotic modules,
which are coupled using mechanical and magnetic coupling.
The goal of the project is to explore existing modular robots,
mainly the Dtto: Modular robot and expanding its capabilities.
The modules are initially tested in a simulation environment
for their feasibility (V-REP) and sensors (ToF) are interfaced to
the modules for smart sensing and decision making.
Snake motion, coupling/decoupling, obstacle detection and
avoidance are achieved in practice.
1) Arduino Nano
2) Bluetooth Module (HC-05)
3) Servo Motors (MG90S,SG90)
4) TOF Sensor (VL53LOX)
5) 2x 1s LiPos in series. 500mAh.
6) RF Module (nRF24L01)
1) Arduino IDE
2) Sloeber Eclipse IDE
3) Coppelia Robotics V-REP Simulator
4) Autodesk Fusion 360
5) PyCharm Community, Python IDE

flowRoot.flowPara: The current working model consists of 4 modules which can succesfully move, connect, attach and detach with other modules.
The VL53L0X ToF distance measurement sensor is added on the female face of one of the modules for obstacle detection.

A Virtual Model has been created on V-REP along with the proximity sensor. Using V-REP remoteAPI in Python, this Virtual Model can be externally controlled via Bluetooth, just like the real world robot. This enables the possibilty of testing out transformations directly in simulation without actually creating a 3D printed model, which saves on expenses if this is implemented as a theme in eYRC.
